ImageDescription: Jared Leto dressed as Choupette and Lizzo
Commentary: In which Lizzo shows how we are all feeling.
Obligatory Anna Wintour photo, and opportunity for me to say that I really don't like her or Karl Lagerfeld as people.
Stormzy seems like a cool dude and he's certainly rocking a very stylish suit. This particular shade of blue is featured a *lot* this evening.
I approve of men in colourful and/or striking suits, but I've included this one mostly because I really respect the commitment that's been made here to plaid pattern-matching.
Again, some of the same shade of blue, with some more quality work with plaid and pattern-matching.
Same shade of blue.
Blue, black, roses and drapey chiffon. Very on theme.

ImageDescription: Cathleen Lynch and Roger Lynch, CEO, Condé Nast (L-R)
Commentary: This dress ticks the blue + roses theme boxes, but I've included it mostly because I think it's a good example of good Older Lady Fashion.
Zero idea who this is, but I like her hair and her outfit is on theme.
This is interesting and I like the matching boots.

I can see what this is going for, but it is fundamentally so ugly and shapeless that it's just hideous. The sleeves look painful, the belt is placed at what appears to be the least flattering spot, and is the fabric at the waist even finished???
This could so easily look like she is wearing a whole bunch of sheets sewn together, but I think the structure of the dress with the collar and cuffs makes it look classy instead.

This is just an odd one. The visible nipples just seem unnecessary - they're not really a feature, just a "oh actually this photo needs nudity warnings, oops". This was also an unusual colour for the evening, though the *plain lines with black tulle* is on theme.

This outfit stands out because it's a bit of an outlying shade of purple for the theme, but it's in my list because of the way her posture is so hunched forwards, and I'm wondering if it's that the underpinnings are the wrong shape for her, or if she's just really uncomfortable. All of her photos have her with this forward shoulders thing going on.
I just love this whole look.
This is just a super cool construction, with the various different shades of fabric. I couldn't see the exact construction details but I really like the texture that the seams create.

Gratuitous Pedro Pascal leg shot because he's the flavour of the month apparently. I am not 100% convinced by Shorts As Formalwear, but it is definitely a step towards normalising Shorts As Business Attire and that red is a Confident Look and I respect it.
This is just a gorgeous dress even though I normally think vinyl can look a bit tacky. I really like the lace over the leg slit.
As you can see, we have moved into the RED section of the evening. This ticks two theme boxes: cutouts and roses.
I liked the overlapping panel layering at the front skirt a lot.
Is it possible that Gabrielle Union is not actually ageless? Surely not.
Two pictures of this outfit, because I can't work out if it's structurally effective or not. Certainly the "sleeves" look uncomfortable. On the other hand, I like the extreme hip shaping.
This just looks like a dress they'd give to Commander Shepard to wear, only less instantly unattractive. I don't mind it; I just can't resist a *Mass Effect* reference.

Three pictures of this one, because it's my favourite outfit of the evening. I like the way it looks like an oversized suit jacket that's been put on inside-out, and I don't mean that as criticism AT ALL -- it's really interesting and looks cool!

The internal structure is also clearly quite impressive, and the asymmetric cutouts look really nice, although the whole effect as an Outfit is far less without the shoulder thing on. (I can't tell if it's all part of the train of the dress, but it might be?)
I am a sucker for shoulderblades, clearly.
The mermaid shape was a recurring theme and I do not like it generally, and I do not like this example because the gathering in the bust makes it look really weirdly shaped.

These two outfits both appear to tick relevant theme boxes while at the same time looking kinda...cheap. I also don't like the way there's a double waistline effect on the floral dress beacuse of the pink rose at the natural waist and then some sort of black tulle band at the hip.

ImageDescription: Agnes Chu, President, Entertainment, Condé Nast and Tom Gilmore (L-R)
Commentary: Just think this is a very elegant dress.
Oversized bows will be another major theme, although they are mostly white, black or pink, and this is slightly unusually apricot.
The fabric reminds me a lot of drapery, but as an ensemble with the yellow jacket, I really like it.
Hard to tell, but I think there are waist cutouts here too.
This is not something I would wear, but I think it's interesting and does a nice take on couture "activewear".
See, that zipper is just fun and decorative! And there's green fleece!
I liked this a lot when I thought it was a crossword dress, but I'm much less keen on it now I realise it says "Karl Lagerfeld" even though in hindsight this is bleedlingly obvious.
The fabric here is interesting, with the sequinned sections and the ruffles. I also like the gloves.
Cool and structural from the front, but then it turns out to be practically backless, which I don't like at all.

Here are shoulderblade details I *don't* like -- the fabric is a straight line and doesn't have any regard for the shape of the back, unlike the way Kylie Jenner's red and blue suit jacket dress is cut at the back.

I don't think this is actually within theme scope (I could also be wrong because I know nothing about Karl Lagerfeld apart from what I've learned from *Maintenance Phase* and the 2023 Met Gala red carpet) but I will always include dark green because there should be more of it in fashion, and I like an Art Nouveau style.
This photo almost got culled for not being sufficiently interesting, but I did really like the way they did the roses here.
This is weird but in a fun, thematic way.
Giant bows (pink and black).
Another *almost got culled for uninterestingness* photo, but I'm interested in the way the hem looks like it's quite thick and structured?
The mermaid shape again, but better: I think because the platform (petals?) section at the top and the exaggerated hips balance out the tail a bit better. Also the bust appears to actually fit her.
Theme boxes: plain lines, black, pale pink, wide open spaces on the torso.
Similarly, but in white and with a cute collar. (The MVP here is clearly THAT COAT though -- look at it! It has sparkles! And arm holes!
Putting the bow at the knees in that contrasting black just makes it look like she's been hobbled in a bondage outfit. Otherwise, it's perfectly fine.
This is a goddess outfit.
I think this is a fun outfit, but also that it would make my nose itch and you'd feel like you were walking in a permanent cloud.
Our Nic, looking happy with Her Keith. I hope she's living her best life. Also if she could put her hair over her shoulders so I could see the bust details on this pls.

This is another thematic one where I don't like the theme and therefore don't like the outfit -- pale pink and visible structural sewing seem antithetical to me, like you're seeing the guts of the garment, but that's clearly the point.

I like the juxtaposition here between the top and bottom. I think what it's reminding me of is the *Buffy* movie - if that's the one I'm thinking of where there's a girl wearing a leather bomber jacket over a pink prom dress?
This fellow just has a lot of style and I like it.

It *fascinates* me how Gwendolyn Christie can span the entire spectrum from "extremely homely" to "absolute goddess" because she is genuinely so unattractive as Brienne of Tarth and yet so spectacularly stylish in *Wednesday* (and here).
Featuring: bare waist and vague corsetry structures; also what appears to be the skin of a giant plush teddy bear.

SImilarly, open (or at least faux-open; there's got to be lining here) boning structures on the torso. The mesh over the arms and shoulders does a nice job of making a strapless dress work on someone who no longer has the smooth skin of youth. I am very curious as to what's going on there with her underbust and waist though -- does a Versace have the same pointy ribcage as me?
Theme boxes: butterflies on tulle, pale pinks. (I don't know why it surprises me that Wendi Deng's Murdoch child is basically grown up now, but it does.)
Yes, I have been describing this to myself as "the lady who's dressed like a lampshade" but also I *really* like this outfit.

I can't work out whether this corsetry fits her *extremely* well and is holding her bust up without squishing it into the centre gap, or if she just has a naturally perky bust and the dress is just acting as a shell. Perhaps a bit of both.
Final note: you can really see how much of a difference the right lighting makes for Black skin, because that first photo of her makes her look washed out, but in the second she is really glowing.
Wide open waist space, black and ivory/white, tulle.

This is another one where there's this weird double waist thing going on -- there's a very defined waist above the skirts, and then there's another "waistline" with that black ribbon at the underbust. I find it confusing.
Presuming from the pose that this is a pregnancy outfit, and I like the way they've turned a Chanel style jacket into a full length dress.
Strong points for making an interesting effort, even though it did not work. Compare with Glenn Close earlier -- here it does just look like they've gathered up some bedsheets.
I love the geometric style lines here.
Wide open waist, tulle with flowers. Robert Pattinson has a kinda half-skirt on, which is interesting. It's nice to see him looking happy in public too, and I hope he's living his best life.
It's not even that she's out of place, it's just that she looks like she's going to an entirely different type of party. I really like the way the external fabric is basically just strings though.
This appears to fit her very well! I like the Ancient Egyptian style skirt, and are those actually piano hinges used as boning??!
This outfit just looks cool.

ImageDescription: Olivia Wilde, Gabriela Hearst, Maude Apatow, and Vanessa Kirby (L-R)
Commentary: Here starts the violin dress section. I couldn't find more pictures of the guitar dress, which saddens me, because it's cool.
Hers is my favourite violin dress, probably because she's got the most striking hair.
If this isn't a pointed statement about people having blood on their hands, I'll be disappointed.
The bloke's outfit seemed so out of place, just because of the colours. Stylistically, I think it's on theme, with the ruffles on the shirt and the style of the jacket collar.
Chanel jacket but for dudes!
It's a nice simple but stylish look for someone who I'd imagine has a hell of a hard time getting formalwear.
More bicycles in everyday life, kthxbai.
Interesting design here with that overskirt with floofy feathers underneath.
Put this one together with Mindy Kaling, because there's such a difference in shape with the top of the bodice near the underarm.
Classic and stylish dress.

Also classic and stylish, which appears to be on brand for Radhika Jones (who even is she when she's not at galas?!?! I don't know....). Don't normally care for drop sleeve and dropped waist, but this all works nicely.
The sharp horizontal line across the upper bust really emphasises how little this dress does for her bust. No shaping, no support, just a lot of visibility and weird shadows.
I like this deconstructed and reconstructed Chanel style. It's *distressed* but without pretending that it's in any way not *Extremely Designer*.
As always, points awarded to any men who show up in something that's not a suit. This is a weird outfit but, sir, you are performing a valuable public service in breaking gender norms.

ImageDescription: Laurie Cumbo and Bobby Digi Olisa (L-R)
Commentary: It's kinda not fair, because I said nice things about the previous outfit and I'm panning this one, despite the fact that there's a lot of similarity (they're white with veils and I don't like them).
...dunno about the jeans.
I'm going to put the blame on pregnancy that they haven't given her enough cup room in the bust here. It's a good choice for waistline though.
We are into the WHITE section of the evening now. There are also a lot more roses.
I don't *quite* gel with this one, but it could be that Aubrey Plaza isn't looking serious and that's confusing me.
There's a lot of white+floof coming up.

Designer here did an excellent job of making her look like a popular representation of an angel. (Not enough eyes to be a biblically-accurate angel though.) I really like the way they've done the varied width on the vertical stripes here.
I dunno what's happening here, but it's exciting!
I've noticed that there's a running theme of having texture created by knotted or twisted fabric.
More twisted fabric, plus fabric flowers.
More twisted fabric. This one is weird, and I wonder if it would be better in a colour other than bright white, so that you could see the textural effects a bit more.
This is absolutely gorgeous. Classic lines, well fitted, lovely textured fabric, and I really like the fringeing at the hem.
Similar style to Dua Lipa's (see previous), but I think this one doesn't come across as well because it's very *white* as opposed to being a more "historical" off-white colour.
Not especially innovative as an outfit, but look at that STYLE, my god.
This one was interesting, because the cutouts reveal way too much about the internal structuring, and it doesn't look good internally.
Honestly a bit too wedding dress for my taste.
This is adorable, but I particularly like the way that her shrug? jacket? coat? isn't all one weight, but there's different bits for hem and sleeves.
Included because it's newsworthy, but I'm just meh about it personally.
Pretty simple dress, with the interest coming from the fabric, the epaulettes, and the cape effect from the underarms.
This person looks like a cat and I had to go check that these were not actual body mods, but it seems like she has an ordinary face in real life, thankfully.
Dude should have stayed in the cat outfit all night and made everyone happy.
Now we are getting into the BLACK AND WHITE/TRAD FORMALWEAR section.

This one I found interesting because of the way the black tie comes down far enough to make it look like the the inside of a zip fly when combined with the fabric flaps at the waistband (which look like the pocket stay insides of a pair of suit trousers).
Black and white + waist cutouts.
As above.
This is extremely *Ophelia* and while it's effective, I really dislike it.

Again with the mermaid shape, although this one I don't mind as much because the tail being white makes it draw the eye less. It would be hard to make Serena Williams look unattractive, because she's physically so impressive. This outfit just has a lot of things going on at once, and I'm not convinced by them all together.
Black and white, cutouts, large fabric bow, flowers.
It's a cool hat though.
And interesting to see the back to see how it stays on properly.
Classic lines and very lovely. I like the shirt collar effect at the waistline.
The decorative zippers are a nice feature (are they actually functional pockets though?? surely not...)
This jacket reminding me that I really want to own a sequinned bomber jacket... Otherwise very unremarkable outfits that meet the brief very well.
Black and white, floofy feathery stuff, and lots of open waist skin. This is also a perfectly fine outfit, although I am curious about the internal structuring on the bodice.
An interesting use of folded fabric to create an on-theme structural effect. I don't really *like* the outfit, but I respect the effort.
Again with visual effects that look like the internals of the garment are on display. (This outfit also reminds me a lot of Morticia, but not in a terrible way.)
This is a nice and stylish pregnancy option. (Again, I'm assuming pregnancy from the pose...)
There'll be a bunch of photos of Kristen Stewart because I like the tomboy/butch look and also (as with Robert Pattinson earlier) I'm glad she seems to be living her best life these days.

Probably the best shot of the full outfit. I like the balloon shaped pants legs here, and also the way that there's a nipped waist by having some sort of close-fitting mesh fabric over the waist instead of continuing all the way down with the heavier shirting.
Couldn't tell if this is an actual tail coat, but I do like women in classic "men's" formalwear.
Very pretty; lots of bling.
Absolutely love this idea of suiting transitioning to a gown.
Very gorgeous. (She deserved an Oscar too.)

Continuing with *Everything Everywhere All At Once*, we have this very stylish creation on Michelle Yeoh, who I once heard described as "the most beautiful woman in the world" when she was in Bond film *Tomorrow Never Dies*, and this description has stuck in my mind ever since then.

This is a great outfit that combines a whole heap of thematic elements (black and white, men's suiting) and has a suit cummerbund and skirt pleating that is very reminiscent of historial martial arts pants. There are also, apparently, pockets?? (This outfit really highlights how little I actually know technically about (a) fashion and (b) Asian fashions, because I don't have the right words to explain what this is and what it's influenced by.)

I think the sleeves are fantastic, and I love the layering that's been done under the overskirt. (The skirts remind me of how our school Japanese teacher used to dress for teaching aikido, which is why I'm making a martial arts comparison, even though I know Michelle Yeoh is not Japanese. I figure there has to be some overlap though in various martial arts traditions in having long loose pants so that your opponent can't see what your feet are doing.

Ah, the very ordinary seeming fellow who is in the news a lot and every time I am disappointed that they're not talking about Peter Davison, Fifth Doctor. Also an excuse for more Michelle Yeoh photos.
This outfit has a similar wide-waistband-skirts-over-pants idea, but without the pleating, I don't get that same martial arts vibe.
A strapless suit!
Ticking all the thematic boxes here.
Final *Everything Everywhere All At Once* reference for this gala, and tbh he's only made it in even though his outfit not especially exciting, because he just looks so very *dapper*.
Another cute Asian man in a suit -- here I'm interested in the crossways pleating? ruffling? that's been done on the top half of the jacket.

Probably the least successful "black and white open fronted skirts" look. This one just doesn't drape well at the front -- the fabric is too stiff, or the white edging shows that the slit doesn't quite go high enough.
This reminds me of high waisted pants that are pulled up waaaaay too high, but I don't actually dislike it.
Another strapless suit jacket (presumably this is a Lagerfeld thing too) but this time with much more bling.

I've always thought of Chanel jackets as being in any colours *other* than black and white, but I guess it makes sense that Lagerfeld would have been into black and white versions, since he was apparently so keen on that colour combo.
Less Chanel-jacket and more actual-suit-in-bouclé fabric.

Again, I can see that this is really committing to THEME, but it is just so absolutely hideous. Some of the feature might have been fine individually, but, combined, they're just a huge clashy mess. I *really* dislike the waistband jockstrap coupled with the super low rise waist on the skirt, and then you add in the black bra under translucent top, and it's just slutty, but not in a fun way.

This, however, is amazing. I love what's been done here with the "oversized" style coat (reminds me of Kylie Jenner's blue and red outfit) and the clothese underneath have interesting elements, rather than being straight suiting.
Theme: sparkles, black and white suiting, asymmetry in lengths, some sort of kilt-ish thing for men.

Bella Ramsey is dressed very clearly to theme, but also in a way that keeps her looking like a kid -- though I looked her up and she is actually 19 now! Makes sense for her image as *The Last Of Us*'s Abby to keep her perceived as younger though, and it may also be her preferred personal style too. (I am a big fan of Bella Ramsey because she's been great in *GoT*, *Hilda* and *The Worst Witch*.)

Something about this outfit doesn't work for me -- I think it's that the jacket is overwhelming her a bi. Double-breasted jackets are designed to create imposing breadth and volume, but I think this would work better if the shoulders were more fitted to her actual frame.
Delightful themed fashion and performance art on and from Janelle Monáe, as always.

(I did find out the other day that she's only a little younger than I am, and now I feel like a terrible underachiever... I recommend seeing *Glass Onion* (the *Knives Out* one) because it's very topical.)

I don't like this one for Lizzo. The lines of pearls (beads?) on the bodice are wobbly and I think that makes her look less impressive, particularly with the skirts being made out of a very drapey and lighter-weight fabric. It's not a bad look though, I just don't prefer it.
Here we have some men with corsetry, or at least very structured garments around the hips. The vertical stripes on this first one are very neat.

The nipped waist is exaggerated here by the cropped jacket (as with Kristen Stewart previously) but I'm pretty sure there's a foundation garment involved, because he goes in a long way at the waist. It could almost be an ABBA tribute band outfit, but I think it looks great.
I guess this is actually "Guest + Marc Metrick". I like what she's done here with the hoop skirt cage, even though she's always going to be overshadowed by Janelle Monáe's version.
Every gala evening needs someone in a Jedi outfit.
This is very *Wednesday* and also very on theme.
This is an example of a dress train that's designed to be viewed on a staircase. It looks bunchy when she's on flat ground, but much better on the staircase.
Can't tell on the corsetry here whether it is functioning well or not, but I think that there's too much room at the bust.
I just like the wings here.
Another outfit that isn't *bad*, I just don't really like it, and I think it's because the white on her torso is so stark.
Her belt here reminds me of a *Star Wars* droid. (The outfit's fine, she looks nice.)
Various black and white outfits that I don't have much to say about, but am including because they look a bit different.
(Actually I really like this one.)
Bonus points for the dude in polka dots.
Meets the theme brief, but is also slightly too brief for my personal sensibilities. It's fine.
The bust here is *not* a good fit for her, which is a shame.
Included because of the way her dress looks like she's got it on backwards.
A series of dudes in black suits with overcoats, but make it *fashion*.
Some specifically Karl Lagerfeld-themed outfits. I like the flares in this one coupled with the wide shoulders on the cape.

ImageDescription: Silvia Venturini Fendi and Delfina Delettrez Fendi (L-R)
Commentary: The fabric is all Lagerfeld faces, which is a neat way to do Themed.
An outfit of great structural integrity, and I really like the way they've done the bust here, and the side ruching looks really good.
Me, bad at faces and pop culture: "Oh hey that must be Beyonce!" (No, it's Rita Ora, as one half of Most Stylish Couple. The other half is a little later.)
Black with mesh that goes into floofy ruffles. Much like Halle Bailey's cape earlier, which was white floofs.
See previous.

This is like Alexandra Daddario, previously (at about #94) - there's a lot of visible bust and underbust and then there's that harsh horizontal line across her hip that contrasts unpleasantly with the fact that humans are actually curvy shapes. This would look immediately better with a curved line at the hip instead.
More open waist. I really like the decorative stitching bows as a nice contrast from the fabric bows.
More waist cutouts. Very stylish.

It's interesting that they went with clear vinyl(?) for the torso here, because I think it doesn't look as good as the waist cutouts that are either flesh or matte fabric. Can see why it would have been easier from a construction prespective though.
Another mermaid, and this one I also don't like, because (to me) the tail grabs the eye and calls so much attention to the fact that I'm convinced she's not able to walk in this.
Kim Kardashian's look, but actually interesting.

I just find this outfit boring because the entire premise is basically only "look at my nice butt", and like, sure, she does have a nice butt, but I'm not that interested in it being the immediate focal point.
A series of black tulle and lace.

ImageDescription: Pierce Brosnan and Keely Shaye Smith (L-R)
Commentary: Pierce Brosnan's suit jacket here is a nice fabric, but I am mostly here for the amazing work that's been done with Keely Shaye Smith's outfit, which is spectacular. The cape is super cute, but just *look* at the invisible corsetry that's creating that physical structure for her. She looks amazing, and it's kinda easy to do that with young skinny people, but she's apparently 59 and has had two kids. I love this outfit on her so much, I cannot even.
Another selection of theme apporpriate outfits that I don't really have anything specific to say about.

I like what they're doing here with the hip shaping (the skirts look like a heart!) and I think I like the semi-visible boning at the bust, though I'm not sure whether that is a busk that actually opens at the front. If it isn't, they maybe could have not made the clasp so visible.

ImageDescription: Idris Elba and Sabrina Dhowre Elba (L-R)
Commentary: An interesting dress here with those Renaissance?? 17th century?? wide panniers, but at the lower hip instead of the waist. It's an interesting look and I don't dislike it. (Her partner here is looking characteristically stylish, but not in any way innovative.)
A series of black dresses with texture and/or structure created through juse of fabric.
This is very beautifully simplistic.
Awesome! Looks like a lighthouse crossed with a disco ball crossed with Barad-dur!
Another dress that seems a little bit out of place, though again, it's not a bad look.
I really like the way they've created shaping by using the contrasting fabrics. Very stylish and lovely.

There's just as much butt going on here as with Kendall Jenner, but the look isn't all *about* "look at my butt" and therefore it's a lot more interesting. (Also, full body suit with sparkles and mask, but it's just more *tasteful* somehow.)
Also a very nice butt.
I absolutely love this look. Probably my favourite menswear look overall.

Like Letitia Wright, she's drowning in this jacket. Which is clearly the intention, because presumably Stella McCartney designed this to wear herself, but I think it makes her look like a little kid playing dress-ups. Just bring the shoulders in to something more resembling your actual shoulders.

I'd like this if it wasn't for the extremely early-2000s super low rise on the skirt, which is similar to Amy Fine Collins from earlier (around #158) but, unlike that one, this outfit actually comes together cohesively.
And it's the other half of *Most Stylish Couple*. This is like loungewear but for red carpets.

Probably my third favourite men's outfit from the evening, but what I don't like about it is that the *back* has a cutout for the back, where you see the shirt instead of the waistcoat. The scarf is great though.
More cutouts, but this time with silver sequins.
This is more simplistic than many of the other ones with super huge cutouts, and I think it works quite well.
Stylish shaping and I like the fringing on the front.

Structural interest created by folding and ruffling suiting/coating fabric. I like it. I wish I could see how that grey triangle hanging down from the waist is supposed to reflect the waist dart?? directly above it.
Dude should have stayed in the cat outfit.
Very stylish military-style jacket ornamentation.
I thought he was holding the fan at first, but it's actually affixed to the outfit, and that's just cool.
